node.text:
Earlier, we were at Canaveral National Seashore. Watch as teams release these rehabilitated sea turtles into the ocean! 🐢 @turtlesfly2 

These sea turtles suffered from cold-stunning in the northeast, were rehabilitated to health and are now swimming in the warm Florida water. This puts them back in the habitat where they should be this time of year, giving them a better chance for survival.

All marine turtle footage/images was obtained with the approval of the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) under conditions not harmful to marine turtles. Footage was acquired while conducting authorized conservation activities pursuant to: FWC 2021 Consent Permit, MTP-21-005 and MTP-21-114.

node.title: Join us as we launch rehabilitated sea turtles back into the ocean!

We’re here at the Launch and Landing Facility as rehabilitated sea turtles arrive from Cape Cod, Mass., and New York to be released in the warmer waters of the Space Coast. 🐢 @turtlesfly2 

These sea turtles suffered from cold-stunning in the northeast, were rehabilitated to health and are now swimming in the warm Florida water. This puts them back in the habitat where they should be this time of year, giving them a better chance for survival.

All marine turtle footage/images was obtained with the approval of the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) under conditions not harmful to marine turtles. Footage was acquired while conducting authorized conservation activities pursuant to: FWC 2021 Consent Permit, MTP-21-005 and MTP-21-114.

Launch Update 🚀 The #Landsat 9 mission is now targeted to launch from Vandenberg Space Force Base in California on a @ULALaunch Atlas V rocket no earlier than Monday, Sept. 27.
 
Landsat 9 is a joint @NASA and @USGS mission that continues the legacy of monitoring Earth’s land and coastal regions, which began with the first Landsat in 1972.
 
Landsat 9 will carry two science instruments – the Operational Land Imager 2 (OLI-2) and the Thermal Infrared Sensor 2 (TIRS-2). OLI-2 will capture observations of the planet in visible, near infrared and shortwave-infrared light. TIRS-2 will measure the thermal infrared radiation, or heat (brightness temperature), of Earth’s surfaces.
 
The launch is managed by NASA’s Launch Services Program based here at Kennedy.

🚀👀 On Sept. 9, 2006, space shuttle Atlantis and its six-member crew launched from Launch Pad 39B to begin the two-day journey to the @ISS on the STS-115 mission.
 
During the 12-day mission, the STS-115 crew resumed construction of the orbiting laboratory after a four year hiatus. The shuttle and station crews worked with ground teams to install a girder-like structure, known as the P3/P4 truss. The 35,000-pound piece included a set of giant solar arrays, batteries and associated electronics.
 
STS-115 Crew: Brent W. Jett, Jr., Christopher J. Ferguson, Heidemarie M. Stefanyshyn-Piper, Joseph R. (Joe) Tanner, Daniel C. Burbank, Steven G. MacLean
 
📸: NASA

Then ➡️ Now
 
On April 29, 2021, the Space Launch System (SLS) core stage arrived at Kennedy Space Center from @nasastennis aboard the Pegasus barge. Teams from Exploration Ground Systems and lead contractor Jacobs then transported the core stage into the Vehicle Assembly Building (VAB) where it was placed atop of the mobile launcher between two solid rocket boosters to prepare for the #Artemis I launch.
 
In the second photo, you’ll see the Orion stage adapter structural test article and the Mass Simulator for Orion stacked on top of the SLS rocket for testing. These test articles represent the mass and weight of the actual Orion stage adapter and Orion spacecraft.
 
Soon, the Orion spacecraft will be transported from the Launch Abort System Facility to the VAB to be integrated with the SLS rocket.
 
Artemis I will be an uncrewed test of Orion and the Space Launch System rocket as an integrated system ahead of crewed flights to the Moon.

Delivered ➡️ student experiments, assortments of cheese and ice cream, new research projects and more!
 
@SpaceX's cargo Dragon spacecraft successfully launched on a Falcon 9 rocket from Kennedy Space Center on Sunday, Aug. 29. The following day, the capsule arrived at the @ISS to drop off more than 4,800 pounds of research, crew supplies and hardware to the international crew.

node.text:
🛡️ Shields up!
 
Right now, teams at Kennedy Space Center are putting the final touches on the Orion spacecraft for the #Artemis I mission. This includes connecting the ogive fairings for the launch abort system (LAS) assembly.
 
The ogive fairings consist of four protective panels and they will shield the crew module from the severe vibrations and sounds it will experience during launch.
 
During Artemis missions, the 44-foot-tall LAS will detach from the spacecraft when it is no longer needed, shortly after launching on the Space Launch System (SLS) rocket, to lighten the journey to the Moon. Although the abort motors will not be active on the uncrewed Artemis I flight test, the system is intended to protect astronauts on future missions if a problem arises during launch or ascent by pulling the spacecraft away from a failing rocket.
 
Once installation of the ogive fairings is complete, the spacecraft will be transported to the Vehicle Assembly Building to be integrated with the SLS rocket ahead of launch.
 
📸: NASA/Kim Shiflett

🚀 This morning at 3:14 a.m. ET, @SpaceX’s Dragon spacecraft successfully launched on a Falcon 9 rocket from Kennedy Space Center for the 23rd commercial resupply services mission! The mission will deliver new science investigations, supplies and equipment to the international crew aboard the @ISS. 

Dragon is slated to arrive at orbiting laboratory around 11 a.m. ET on Monday, Aug. 30. The spacecraft will spend about a month at the station before autonomously undocking and returning to Earth, splashing down in the Atlantic Ocean with about 4,200 pounds of research and return cargo.

These four astronauts will soon launch to the @ISS from Kennedy Space Center on @NASA’s @SpaceX Crew-3 mission ➡️ Raja Chari, Thomas Mashburn, Kayla Barron and Matthias Maurer
 
Targeted to launch no earlier than Oct. 31, Crew-3 will mark the third crew rotation mission on SpaceX’s human space transportation system and its fourth flight with astronauts, including the Demo-2 test flight, to the orbiting laboratory through the Commercial Crew Program. When Chari, Marshburn, Barron and Maurer arrive at the orbiting laboratory, they will become expedition crew members for the duration of their six-month science mission. The crew will have a slight overlap with the Crew-2 astronauts, who arrived April 24.
 
📸: NASA/Josh Valcarcel

🚀🤩 #OTD in 1996, space shuttle Atlantis was rolled out to Launch Pad 39A in preparation for launch of the STS-79 mission. 

Originally set to lift off on July 31, Atlantis was rolled back to the Vehicle Assembly Building twice due to hurricane threats and to switch out the twin solid rocket boosters. The STS-79 mission launched on Sept. 16, 1996, lasted a little more than 10 days and traveled 3.9 million miles.
 
#DYK❓ You can find this same space shuttle on display at @KennedySpaceCenter Visitor Complex! Have you come nose-to-nose with Atlantis? Let us know in the comments below ⬇️

Landsat 9 🌎➡️ Continuing 50 years of eyes on our changing planet
 
In one month, Landsat 9 will launch on a @ULALaunch Atlas V 401 rocket from Space Launch Complex 3 at Vandenberg Space Force Base in California! The launch is managed by NASA’s Launch Services Program, based here at Kennedy Space Center.
 
This mission will continue the legacy of monitoring Earth’s land and coastal regions that began with the first Landsat in 1972. Once fully commissioned in orbit, Landsat 9 will replace Landsat 7, and join its sister satellite Landsat 8 to collect images from across the planet every eight days. This calibrated data will continue the Landsat program’s critical role in monitoring land use and helping decision makers manage essential resources including crops, water resources and forests.
 
👀 What would you do with 50 years of Earth observations?
